10 §24.14. Adolescent literacy instruction and assessment; parental notification;
11 professional development
12 A. For purposes of this Section:
13 (1) "Adolescent literacy" means the development and application of reading,
14 writing, language, and comprehension skills necessary for students in grades four
15 through eight to access, understand, analyze, and produce grade-level text across all
16 subject areas.
17 (2) "Adolescent literacy intervention course" means a professional learning
18 course that includes all of the components of an adolescent literacy professional
19 development course as defined in Paragraph (3) of this Subsection and all of the
20 following:
21 (a) Comprehensive training on the science of reading, including explicit and
22 systematic instruction in phonological and phonemic awareness, phonics, including
23 decoding and encoding, fluency, vocabulary, syntax, and comprehension.
24 (b) Approaches to assist educators in determining which students may be at
25 risk for development of reading and writing difficulties, including dyslexia,
26 dysgraphia, and other learning differences.
27 (c) Training in the identification of and the use of appropriate interventions,
28 accommodations, and teaching techniques for students with reading and writing
29 difficulties, including dyslexia, dysgraphia, and other learning differences.
